MoodMapper_Final

Author

Richa Jain

Mood Mapper

ABSTRACT

The aim of this project is to use term frequency-inverse document frequency (TF-IDF) and a random forest model to predict the sentiment of documents. This project uses a dataset found on Kaggle that includes a column ‘Description’ and a column ‘Mood.’ TF-IDF and random forest are used to train a model that will be able to use the description to predict the mood. The goal is to see how accurate this method is in predicting the same mood as in the actual dataset. This process ultimately revealed approximately a 45% accuracy, so TF-IDF and random forest may not be the best approach in predicting mood for the given descriptions.

DATA

Link to dataset: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/praveengovi/emotions-dataset-for-nlp/data The dataset includes a column for ‘Description’ and a column for ‘Mood.’ Kaggle also includes a train.txt file for training the model and a test.txt file for testing the model. Kaggle describes the data as a collection of documents and its associated emotions.

INTRODUCTION

The goal of this project is to determine the emotion of an individual based on a short description. In the dataset, descriptions are of varying lengths and the associated emotion is one of the following: sadness, anger, love, surprise, fear, or joy.

To do this prediction, I used term frequency-inverse document frequency (TF-IDF) and a random forest model. TF-IDF is a common natural language processing method that determines the importance of words or phrases in a document. In machine learning, this ‘document’ is called a corpus. The term frequency part looks at the frequency of terms. For this project, I determined the number of times a specific words appeared in the document. The inverse document frequency part determines how common each word is in the corpus.

Term frequency-inverse document frequency (TF-IDF) is used to measure the importance of words in a document. This goes through all the words that are seen in the Description column and creates a whole column for each and every word. It then gives a 1 or 0 for whether that word occurs in the Description for that row or not, respectively.

A random forest model is a common machine learning algorithm. It is made up of multiple decision trees that can be used for classification in order to determine what group our observation belongs to. For the purpose of this project, we use random forest to determine what mood/emotion our description belongs to. The random forest algorithm grows multiple trees that are ultimately merged to get a final prediction value.

METHODS

The initial part of this project is to load the libraries, read in the data, and format it. I also added in a column to label each emotion a numeric value from 1-6.

Sadness: 1 Anger: 2 Love: 3 Surprise: 4 Fear: 5 Joy: 6

The next step was to clean up the text by converting the entire dataset to lowercase. From there, I built the TF-IDF matrix. R has a library called tm that converts the data to lowercase, removes stop words, removes punctuation, and then finally creates the document term matrix. It results in a table that has a column for each word that occurs in the description column of the original dataset. It then has a 0 or 1 for whether that row (that observation) has that word in it’s description or not.

When the TF-IDF was originally built, it was not working in the random forest model. There was an error in the model dataframe whether the variable/each column (word) was deemed “incorrect.” According to Stack Overflow, a solution to this problem is to change the names of each feature (column) and append something like “_c” to the end.

The next step in this process was to determine the number of trees for the random forest model. When I originally ran a random forest model using R’s randomForest package, it took over 24 hours to run. The default number of trees in this model was 500. I learned that R has a different library called ‘ranger’ that is a fast implementation of random forests. It uses parallel processing to increase the training speed of the model. Once I used this package, I decided to create a sequence of different values to test for my number of trees and create a plot for accuracy vs trees. I created a range from 10 to 150 with increments by 10. Utimately, I learned that around 120 trees, the accuracy of the model plateaus out. The number of trees used in this model is 150 (Note: This part takes 20 minutes to run). The way I checked accuracy was using the out of bag value.

Out of bag error is used to estimate the performance of a random forest model. Within each tree, the “out of bag” observations are used as the test to evaluate the tree. Out of bag means the observations not used for that tree. At the end, all the predictions on the out of bag observations of the trees are aggregated to give an estimate of the performance. In general, you want a small out of bag error because that means the model is making accurate predictions.

EVALUATION

The next step for this project was to build the model with the right number of trees, generate the predictions on the test set, and then evaluate the model.

After running the loop, I determined the best number of trees to be 150. I ran a ranger (a random forest) model on the TF-IDF dataset where the label (numeric value for emotion) is the dependent variable that we are trying to predict.

Next, I read in the test dataset and formatted it the same way as the training dataset. (Note: This part takes about 8 minutes to run) I ran a for loop through each description in the dataset to convert it to lowercase, remove punctuation, and remove stop words. This for loop also generated a TF-IDF for each description separately and used the TF-IDF from the training dataset as a dictionary and reference. I then predicted the value of the emotion/label for this TF-IDF. The reason I did this row by row was to get the individual predicted label for each row. Ranger also returns multiple predictions per tree so the best solution to combine this was to choose the most occuring prediction as the overall prediction.
